social_media$Mood_Productivity <- ifelse(test=social_media$Mood_Productivity == 'Yes', yes="Productive", no="Not Productive") 
social_media_reg <- social_media[, c("Instagram_Usage", "LinkedIn_Usage",   "Snapchat_Usage", "Twitter_Usage",  "Whatsapp_Usage", "Reddit", "Youtube_Usage",    "OTT", "Mood_Productivity", "Tired_waking_up_in_morning", "Trouble_falling_asleep")]

1)Model Development

# Recode Mood_Productivity column
social_media_reg$Mood_Productivity <- ifelse(social_media_reg$Mood_Productivity == "Not Productive", 0, 1)
# Fit logistic regression model
logistic_reg <- glm(Mood_Productivity ~ Instagram_Usage + LinkedIn_Usage + Snapchat_Usage + Twitter_Usage + Whatsapp_Usage + Youtube_Usage + OTT + Trouble_falling_asleep + Tired_waking_up_in_morning, data = social_media_reg, family = "binomial")

# Summary of the logistic regression model
summary(logistic_reg)

The p-values for all predictor variables (“Instagram_Hours”, “LinkedIn_Hours”, “Snapchat_Hours”, etc.) are uniformly non-significant, with values equal to 1. This suggests that there is insufficient evidence to support the idea that any of these variables significantly influence mood productivity.

The dataframe presents probabilities for moods being labeled as either “Yes” or “No”. Analysis of the table suggests a bias towards classification as “Yes”. However, this plot highlights the deficiencies in the model’s performance, indicating its inadequacy.

Every value within the pdata object signifies the predicted probability of the mood being labeled as “Yes” for the corresponding observation in your dataset.

dataF <- as.factor(ifelse(test=as.numeric(data>0.5) == 0, yes="Not Productive", no="Productive"))

The model exhibits flawless accuracy, suggesting possible overfitting owing to the limited dataset size. The imbalance in data, with predominantly “Yes” labels for mood productivity, underscores bias concerns. Consequently, accurately gauging mood productivity based solely on social media usage remains a formidable challenge.
